  "stage": {
    "id": "stage_2_blocks",
    "stageNumber": 2,
    "title": "Stage 2: Assembling the Building Blocks",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "multi_head_attention",
        "title": "Combining 8 Heads",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- parallel subspaces\n- output projection\n\nMultiHead(Q,K,V) = Concat(head₁,...,head₈)Wᴼ. With h=8 and dᵥ=64, concat gives 512-dim which the output projection Wᴼ maps back to d_model=512.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "add_and_norm",
        "title": "Residual Connections & LayerNorm",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- residual shortcut\n- LayerNorm over d_model\n\nThe output of each sublayer is LayerNorm(x + Sublayer(x)). LayerNorm normalizes over the d_model=512 dimension (not batch), making it independent of batch size — key for variable-length sequences.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "ffn_block",
        "title": "The Feed-Forward Sublayer",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- d_ff=2048\n- per-position identical\n\nFFN(x)=max(0,xW₁+b₁)W₂+b₂ with W₁∈ℝ^{512×2048}. The 4× expansion (d_ff/d_model) is a design choice the authors validated empirically; it's the same ratio used in GPT and BERT.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "encoder_block",
        "title": "Stacking the Encoder",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- N=6 identical layers\n- self-attention\n\nSix identical encoder layers each contain: Multi-Head Self-Attention → Add&Norm → FFN → Add&Norm. Depth lets the model build increasingly abstract representations, analogous to layers in CNNs.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "decoder_block",
        "title": "Adding the Decoder",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- causal mask\n- cross-attention\n\nEach decoder block has 3 sublayers: masked self-attention (can't see future tokens), cross-attention over encoder output, and FFN — each wrapped with Add&Norm. The mask enforces autoregressive generation.",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-2",
      "question": "What does the causal mask in the decoder's self-attention do? Answer with a number.",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "Masks padding tokens",
        "Prevents each position from attending to future positions",
        "Reduces memory by masking half the attention matrix"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Prevents each position from attending to future positions",
      "position": {
        "x": 18,
        "y": 7
      }
    },
